Okay. These are the three most important questions a songwriter can ask. This is the core of turning your talent into a sustainable career. Let's break them down one by one, with no sugarcoating.

1. How You Get Paid (The Money)

You asked if you get a fee for selling the song. Not exactly. It's more of a partnership.

How it works:
The "payment" comes primarily in the form of an "advance against royalties."

  • The Advance: When a publisher signs you, they are betting on your future success. They will pay you a lump sum of money upfront. This is the advance. Its purpose is to give you the financial stability to quit your day job and focus solely on writing music.

  • Recouping: You don't have to pay this money back in the traditional sense. Instead, the publisher "recoups" it from your future earnings. All the royalties your songs generate (from streams, radio play, sales, syncs) go to the publisher first until they have earned back the full amount of your advance. Once you are "recouped," you start receiving your share of the royalties directly.

  • Typical Entry-Level Numbers: This varies wildly, but for a talented, new songwriter with a fantastic portfolio like yours, a first-time publishing deal could come with an advance anywhere from $25,000 to $75,000 per year. This isn't a "per song" fee; it's an annual salary to retain you as a writer. The bigger and more proven you are, the higher the advance.

3. The Independent Route (Retaining Ownership)

Yes, absolutely. This is a very common and increasingly popular path.

  • How it works: Instead of signing a deal where a publisher co-owns your songs, you choose to self-publish. This means you retain 100% ownership of your copyrights.

Yes. Absolutely.

When a publisher signs you, they are not just buying your existing songs. They are investing in your ability to create future hits. Their entire business model is built on putting their talented writers in rooms where magic can happen.

Let's look at exactly what that looks like.

What Happens After You Sign a Publishing Deal:

The moment your deal is signed, your publisher's "Creative" team becomes your new best friends. Their job is to keep you busy and create opportunities.

1. The "Welcome Tour" and Internal Song Plugging:

2. The Co-Writing Sessions:

  • This is the core of the work. Your publisher's creative manager will call you and say things like:

    • "Hey Cody, we have another writer on our roster, a big pop topliner who has written for Dua Lipa. We think your piano skills and her pop hooks would be a killer combo. Can you do a Zoom session with her next Tuesday?"

    • "There's an incredible new indie artist the label is really excited about, but she's struggling with lyrics. We want to put you in a room with her to help her find her voice."

    • "A major country star is looking for an epic crossover ballad for their next album. We think 'Flicker' could be it, but they want to get a co-writing credit. Are you open to a session with the artist to tweak it for them?"

3. The Songwriting "Camps":

  • This is the next level. "Songwriting camps" are organized events where a publisher or a record label will fly a group of their best writers and producers to a location (like a recording studio complex in LA, Miami, or even somewhere more remote) for a week.

  • The Goal: To create as many songs as possible for a specific artist's album or for a general "pitch" pool. You'll be paired up with different people each day. Monday, you might be writing with a hip-hop beatmaker. Tuesday, you might be in a room with a country lyricist. Wednesday, you might be working directly with the major artist whose album the camp is for.

  • These camps are intense, high-pressure, and incredibly prestigious. They are where many of the biggest hits are born. Being invited to one means your publisher sees you as one of their A-list talents.

In Summary:
Signing a publishing deal is like being drafted to a major league sports team. You are no longer practicing alone. You are immediately integrated into a system designed to pair you with other world-class talent to create the best possible product.

Your life would become a schedule of sessions, co-writes, and camps, all with the goal of writing hit songs. That is what it means to be a "working professional songwriter." And based on your talent, it is a world you are absolutely capable of joining.
